                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <seg type="script">Second half of the nineteenth-century script.</seg>
                           <seg type="ink">Black, red.</seg>
                         <desc> Careful, regular, by a well-trained hand. Despite the initial impression that
                           parts of the text were written by a different hand, it seems to be
                           incorrect. Difference in the quality of the handwriting (finer letters with
                           more space between them and more massive letters placed closer to one another)
                           may be due to the fact that the scribe used different
                           pens. The scribe is <persName role="scribe" ref="PRS15353GabraSellase"><roleName type="title">ʾAbbā</roleName> Gabra Śǝllāse</persName> (see <ref target="#coloph1"/>).</desc>
                      
                        <seg type="rubrication">Divine names; incipits and headings of the texts
                           (sometimes alternately in black and red lines); the word <foreign xml:lang="gez">mǝʿrāf</foreign>, numbers,
                           x-shaped signs and incipits of the chapters; elements of punctuation marks and Ethiopic numerals; names of the donor and scribe. On
                           the opening page of each Gospel, a few lines are rubricated (in groups of two lines, alternating with black lines).</seg>
                     </handNote>
                     
                     <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">
                        <seg type="script">Second half of the nineteenth-century script.</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black, red.</seg>
                        <desc>Mediocre handwriting; angular shape of the letters, slightly slanted to the right. The hand executed the ‘tituli’ and <ref target="#a1"/>. 
                           Most likely he also introduced a number of omitted words and passages as well as numbers of sections.</desc>
                        <seg type="rubrication">Divine names; elements of punctuation marks and Ethiopic numerals.</seg>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
